definition.value: A marine macrodiolide that is isolated from the sponge Mycale hentscheli and exhibits anticancer and antiviral properties
An all-trans-4-hydroxyretinoate that is the conjugate base of (S)-all-trans-4-hydroxyretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of all-trans-4-oxoretinoic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A spirocyclic sesquiterpenoid that is isolated from the red alga Laurencia glandulifera.

A carboxylic ester obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of (6E)-8-methylnon-6-enoic acid with the benzylic hydroxy group of vanillyl alcohol. A non-pungent analogue of capsaicin with a similar biological profile.
A macrolide antibiotic that is 20-oxotylactone having a beta-D-mycaminosyl residue attached at position 5.
A diterpene alkaloid and potent cardiotoxin that is found in the leaves and berries of the European yew (Taxus baccata).
A tricyclic sesquiterpenoid that is isolated from the Australian marine alga Laurencia filiformis.
An omega-oxo fatty acid derived from hexadecanoic acid.
A 2,5-dihydro-1,3-thiazole carrying carboxy-, methyl- and (2-phosphonooxy)ethylidene-substituents at positions 2, 4 and 5 respectively.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of 3',5'-cyclic IMP arising from deprotonation of the free phosphate OH group; major species at pH 7.3.
A tembetarine obtained by methylation of the tertiary amino function of (R)-reticuline.
A tembetarine obtained by methylation of the tertiary amino function of (R)-reticuline.

A synthetic disaccharide phosphate consisting of an alpha-D-GlcNAc-(1->3)-alpha-D-GlcNAc disaccharide linked glycosidically to O-2 of D-glyceric acid and connected to a 5-aminopentyl linker via a phospho group at O-6 of the reducing-end residue. Synthesized for immobilization on microarray surfaces and conjugation to carrier proteins as a potential vaccine candidate to protect from Clostridium difficile infections.

A tetrasaccharide derivative with a dimeric structure in which two 2-O-[N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminyl-(1->3)-N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminyl]-D-glyceric acid units are linked via a phosphodiester bridge, the reducing-end GlcNAc residue also being connected at O-6 to a 5-aminopentyl linker via a further phosphodiester linkage.

An organic group derived from alpha-D-GlcpNAc-(1->3)-[P-6-[CH2]5NH2]-alpha-D-GlcpNAc-(1->2)-D-GroA (CHEBI:134201) in which the 5-aminopentyl linker is replaced by a 6-(pentylamino)hexanamido one. When linked to the diphtheria toxin mutant 197CRM, it shows potential as a Clostridium difficile vaccine candidate.
An organophosphate oxoanion that is the conjugate base of guanylyl-(3'->5')-cytidine, obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate group.
The D-enantiomer of 2-methylserine.
A hydroxy-amino acid that is serine which is substituted by a methyl group at position 2.
An L-alpha-amino acid residue derived from N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosaminyl-L-tyrosine.
Any benzylisoquinoline alkaloid that has a structure based on 4H-dibenzo[de,g]quinoline or its 3-methyl derivative.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (R)-laudanosine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (R)-tetrahydropapaverine, obtained by protonation of the secondary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (R)-glaucine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A aporphine alkaloid that is the quaternary ammonium ion obtained by methylation of the tertiary amino group of (S)-glaucine.
A ketohexose that is 1,2,4,5,6-pentahydroxyhexan-3-one having L-xylo-configuration.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of bulbocapnine, obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A group of trihydroxy-5beta-cholanic acids that are the 6,7-diastereoisomers of 3alpha,6,7-trihydroxy-5beta-cholan-24-oic acid.
A aporphine alkaloid that is the quaternary ammonium ion obtained by methylation of the tertiary amino group of bulbocapnine.
A monounsaturated fatty aldehyde that is decanal which has undergone formal dehydrogenation to introduce a double bond at unspecified position.
A member of the class of 1,3-thiazolemonocarboxylic acids that is 1,3-thiazole-4-carboxylic acid in which the hydrogen at position 2 has been replaced by a 6-hydroxy-1,3-benzothiazol-2-yl group.
A member of the class of pteridines that is lpteridine-4,7(3H,8H)-dione carrying additional amino, 1-hydroxypropyl and methyl substituents at positions 2, 6 and 8.
A defensive steroid lactone that is produced by males of the species Photinus pyralis.
A semiquinone derived from a 1,4-benzoquinone by formal addition of one hydrogen atom with its electron, or from the removal of one hydrogen atom with its electron from a hydroquinone.

A linear tetrasaccharide derivative consisting of N-acetyl-alpha-D-mannosaminyl, N-acetyl-alpha-L-fucosaminyl, N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl and  alpha-D-galactosyl residues linked sequentially (1->3), (1->3) and (1->4), and at the reducing end linked glycosidically to a 5-aminopentyl group.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as icosanoyl (arachidoyl) and hexadecanoyl (palmitoyl) respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as docosanoyl and tetradecanoyl respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as docosanoyl and pentadecanoyl respectively.

A linear trisaccharide derivative consisting of N-acetyl-alpha-L-fucosaminyl, N-acetyl-alpha-D-galactosaminyl and alpha-D-galactosyl residues linked sequentially (1->3) and (1->4), and at the reducing end linked glycosidically to a 5-aminopentyl group.
A phosphatidylcholine 34:0 in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as icosanoyl (arachidyl) and tetradecanoyl (myristoyl) respectively.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine in which the 1- and 2-acyl groups are specified as pentadecanoyl and docosanoyl respectively.
A monocarboxylic acid anion resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of (4S)-4,16-dihydroxyretinoic acid.
A family of gamma-lactones that are isolated from the seeds of Annona atemoya.
A family of gamma-lactones that are isolated from the seeds of Annona muricata and Annona nutans.
A phosphatidic acid in which one acyl group has 16 carbons and is fully saturated while the other has 18 carbons and 1 double bond.
A phosphatidic acid in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 36 carbons and 2 double bonds.
A phosphatidylethanolamine in which the two acyl groups contain a total of 37 carbons and no double bonds.
